|[[United States District Court for the District of New Mexico]]

|Lawsuit regarding the use of drop boxes in the 2020 elections. On December 14, 2020, the Trump campaign filed a lawsuit against the [[Maggie Toulouse Oliver|New Mexico Secretary of State]] over the use of ballot drop-boxes for the 2020 presidential election. However, on January 11, 2021, five days after [[2021 United States Electoral College count|Congress certified]] the results for Joe Biden, the campaign dropped the lawsuit. <ref> https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/president-donald-trumps-campaign-drops-new-mexico-election-lawsuit/ar-BB1cFoli </ref> Trump attorney Mark Caruso cited “events that have transpired since the inception of this lawsuit” in a three-page motion as the reason for dropping the lawsuit. However, the motion still allows for revisiting these concerns in the future. <ref> https://apnews.com/article/election-2020-donald-trump-state-elections-lawsuits-general-elections-66d53e1e68b331c8b0bd86887dfc252b </ref>

United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit

|Lawsuit seeking de-certification of Arizona results, litigated by Sidney Powell. The judge ruled that the plaintiffs lacked legal standing; their fraud allegations were vague and implausible, and their evidence was unreliable or irrelevant.
